[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] When the resulting series of bits is reread according to the serialization format, it can be used to create a semantically identical clone of the original object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For many complex objects, such as those that make extensive use of references, this process is not straightforward.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Serialization of objects does not include any of their associated methods with which they were previously linked.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] This process of serializing an object is also called *marshalling* in some situations.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The opposite operation, extracting a data structure from a series of bytes, is ***deserialization*** (also called ***unserialization*** or ***unmarshalling***).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In networking equipment hardware, the part that is responsible for serialization and deserialization is commonly called SerDes.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For some of these features to be useful, architecture independence must be maintained.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For example, for maximal use of distribution, a computer running on a different hardware architecture should be able to reliably reconstruct a serialized data stream, regardless of endianness.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] This means that the simpler and faster procedure of directly copying the memory layout of the data structure cannot work reliably for all architectures.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Serializing the data structure in an architecture-independent format means preventing the problems of byte ordering, memory layout, or simply different ways of representing data structures in different programming languages.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Inherent to any serialization scheme is that, because the encoding of the data is by definition serial, extracting one part of the serialized data structure requires that the entire object be read from start to end, and reconstructed.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In many applications, this linearity is an asset, because it enables simple, common I/O interfaces to be utilized to hold and pass on the state of an object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In applications where higher performance is an issue, it can make sense to expend more effort to deal with a more complex, non-linear storage organization.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Even on a single machine, primitive pointer objects are too fragile to save because the objects to which they point may be reloaded to a different location in memory.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] To deal with this, the serialization process includes a step called *unswizzling* or *pointer unswizzling*, where direct pointer references are converted to references based on name or position.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The deserialization process includes an inverse step called *pointer swizzling*.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] It is not necessary to actually build the prior copy because differences can be detected on the fly, a technique called differential execution.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] This is useful in the programming of user interfaces whose contents are time-varying — graphical objects can be created, removed, altered, or made to handle input events without necessarily having to write separate code to do those things.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Serialization breaks the opacity of an abstract data type by potentially exposing private implementation details.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Trivial implementations which serialize all data members may violate encapsulation.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] To discourage competitors from making compatible products, publishers of proprietary software often keep the details of their programs' serialization formats a trade secret.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Some deliberately obfuscate or even encrypt the serialized data.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Yet, interoperability requires that applications be able to understand each other's serialization formats.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Therefore, remote method call architectures such as CORBA define their serialization formats in detail.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Many institutions, such as archives and libraries, attempt to future proof their backup archives—in particular, database dumps—by storing them in some relatively human-readable serialized format.
