[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Storable includes functions to serialize and deserialize Perl data structures to and from files or Perl scalars.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In addition to serializing directly to files, `Storable` includes the `freeze` function to return a serialized copy of the data packed into a scalar, and `thaw` to deserialize such a scalar.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] This is useful for sending a complex data structure over a network socket or storing it in a database.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] When serializing structures with `Storable`, there are network safe functions that always store their data in a format that is readable on any computer at a small cost of speed.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] These functions are named `nstore`, `nfreeze`, etc.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] There are no "n" functions for deserializing these structures — the regular `thaw` and `retrieve` deserialize structures serialized with the "`n`" functions and their machine-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] PHP originally implemented serialization through the built-in `serialize()` and `unserialize()` functions.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] PHP can serialize any of its data types except resources (file pointers, sockets, etc.).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The built-in `unserialize()` function is often dangerous when used on completely untrusted data.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For objects, there are two "magic methods" that can be implemented within a class — `__sleep()` and `__wakeup()` — that are called from within `serialize()` and `unserialize()`, respectively, that can clean up and restore an object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For example, it may be desirable to close a database connection on serialization and restore the connection on deserialization; this functionality would be handled in these two magic methods.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] They also permit the object to pick which properties are serialized.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Since PHP 5.1, there is an object-oriented serialization mechanism for objects, the `Serializable` interface.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Prolog's *term* structure, which is the only data structure of the language, can be serialized out through the built-in predicate `write_term/3` and serialized-in through the built-in predicates `read/1` and `read_term/2`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The resulting stream is uncompressed text (in some encoding determined by configuration of the target stream), with any free variables in the term represented by placeholder variable names.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The predicate `write_term/3` is standardized in the ISO Specification for Prolog (ISO/IEC 13211-1) on pages 59 ff.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Therefore it is expected that terms serialized-out by one implementation can be serialized-in by another without ambiguity or surprises.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In practice, implementation-specific extensions (e.g.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] SWI-Prolog's dictionaries) may use non-standard term structures, so interoperability may break in edge cases.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] As examples, see the corresponding manual pages for SWI-Prolog, SICStus Prolog, GNU Prolog.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Whether and how serialized terms received over the network are checked against a specification (after deserialization from the character stream has happened) is left to the implementer.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Prolog's built-in Definite Clause Grammars can be applied at that stage.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The core general serialization mechanism is the `pickle` standard library module, alluding to the database systems term *pickling* to describe data serialization (*unpickling* for *deserializing*).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Pickle uses a simple stack-based virtual machine that records the instructions used to reconstruct the object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] It is a cross-version customizable but unsafe (not secure against erroneous or malicious data) serialization format.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Malformed or maliciously constructed data, may cause the deserializer to import arbitrary modules and instantiate any object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The standard library also includes modules serializing to standard data formats: `json` (with built-in support for basic scalar and collection types and able to support arbitrary types via encoding and decoding hooks).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] `plistlib` (with support for both binary and XML property list formats).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] `xdrlib` (with support for the External Data Representation (XDR) standard as described in RFC 1014).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Finally, it is recommended that an object's `__repr__` be evaluable in the right environment, making it a rough match for Common Lisp's `print-object`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Not all object types can be pickled automatically, especially ones that hold operating system resources like file handles, but users can register custom "reduction" and construction functions to support the pickling and unpickling of arbitrary types.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Pickle was originally implemented as the pure Python `pickle` module, but, in versions of Python prior to 3.0, the `cPickle` module (also a built-in) offers improved performance (up to 1000 times faster).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The `cPickle` was adapted from the Unladen Swallow project.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In Python 3, users should always import the standard version, which attempts to import the accelerated version and falls back to the pure Python version.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] R has the function `dput` which writes an ASCII text representation of an R object to a file or connection.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] A representation can be read from a file using `dget`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] More specific, the function `serialize` serializes an R object to a connection, the output being a raw vector coded in hexadecimal format.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The `unserialize` function allows to read an object from a connection or a raw vector.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] REBOL will serialize to file (`save/all`) or to a `string!` (`mold/all`).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Strings and files can be deserialized using the polymorphic `load` function.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] `RProtoBuf` provides cross-language data serialization in R, using Protocol Buffers.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Ruby includes the standard module `Marshal` with 2 methods `dump` and `load`, akin to the standard Unix utilities `dump` and `restore`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] These methods serialize to the standard class `String`, that is, they effectively become a sequence of bytes.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Some objects cannot be serialized (doing so would raise a `TypeError` exception): bindings, procedure objects, instances of class IO, singleton objects and interfaces.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] If a class requires custom serialization (for example, it requires certain cleanup actions done on dumping / restoring), it can be done by implementing 2 methods: `_dump` and `_load`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The instance method `_dump` should return a `String` object containing all the information necessary to reconstitute objects of this class and all referenced objects up to a maximum depth given as an integer parameter (a value of -1 implies that depth checking should be disabled).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The class method `_load` should take a `String` and return an object of this class.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] `Serde` is the most widely used library, or crate, for serialization in Rust which provides the `Serialize` and `Deserialize` traits.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In general, non-recursive and non-sharing objects can be stored and retrieved in a human readable form using the `storeOn:`/`readFrom:` protocol.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The `storeOn:` method generates the text of a Smalltalk expression which – when evaluated using `readFrom:` – recreates the original object.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] This scheme is special, in that it uses a procedural description of the object, not the data itself.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] It is therefore very flexible, allowing for classes to define more compact representations.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] However, in its original form, it does not handle cyclic data structures or preserve the identity of shared references (i.e. two references a single object will be restored as references to two equal, but not identical copies).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For this, various portable and non-portable alternatives exist.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Some of them are specific to a particular Smalltalk implementation or class library.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] There are several ways in Squeak Smalltalk to serialize and store objects.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The easiest and most used are `storeOn:/readFrom:` and binary storage formats based on `SmartRefStream` serializers.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] In addition, bundled objects can be stored and retrieved using `ImageSegments`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Both provide a so-called "binary-object storage framework", which support serialization into and retrieval from a compact binary form.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Both handle cyclic, recursive and shared structures, storage/retrieval of class and metaclass info and include mechanisms for "on the fly" object migration (i.e. to convert instances which were written by an older version of a class with a different object layout).
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The APIs are similar (storeBinary/readBinary), but the encoding details are different, making these two formats incompatible.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] However, the Smalltalk/X code is open source and free and can be loaded into other Smalltalks to allow for cross-dialect object interchange.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Object serialization is not part of the ANSI Smalltalk specification.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] As a result, the code to serialize an object varies by Smalltalk implementation.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] For instance, a serialized object created in Squeak Smalltalk cannot be restored in Ambrai Smalltalk.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Consequently, various applications that do work on multiple Smalltalk implementations that rely on object serialization cannot share data between these different implementations.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] These applications include the MinneStore object database and some RPC packages.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] A solution to this problem is SIXX, which is a package for multiple Smalltalks that uses an XML-based format for serialization.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] The Swift standard library provides two protocols, `Encodable` and `Decodable` (composed together as `Codable`), which allow instances of conforming types to be serialized to or deserialized from JSON, property lists, or other formats.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Default implementations of these protocols can be generated by the compiler for types whose stored properties are also `Decodable` or `Encodable`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] PowerShell implements serialization through the built-in cmdlet `Export-CliXML`.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] `Export-CliXML` serializes .NET objects and stores the resulting XML in a file.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] To reconstitute the objects, use the `Import-CliXML` cmdlet, which generates a deserialized object from the XML in the exported file.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Deserialized objects, often known as "property bags" are not live objects; they are snapshots that have properties, but no methods.
[src:apache-parquet/data-serialization] Two dimensional data structures can also be (de)serialized in CSV format using the built-in cmdlets `Import-CSV` and `Export-CSV`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A **database index** is a data structure that improves the speed of data retrieval operations on a database table at the cost of additional writes and storage space to maintain the index data structure.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indexes are used to quickly locate data without having to search every row in a database table every time said table is accessed.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indexes can be created using one or more columns of a database table, providing the basis for both rapid random lookups and efficient access of ordered records.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index is a copy of selected columns of data, from a table, that is designed to enable very efficient search.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index normally includes a "key" or direct link to the original row of data from which it was copied, to allow the complete row to be retrieved efficiently.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Some databases extend the power of indexing by letting developers create indexes on column values that have been transformed by functions or expressions.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] For example, an index could be created on `upper(last_name)`, which would only store the upper-case versions of the `last_name` field in the index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Another option sometimes supported is the use of partial index, where index entries are created only for those records that satisfy some conditional expression.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A further aspect of flexibility is to permit indexing on user-defined functions, as well as expressions formed from an assortment of built-in functions.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Most database software includes indexing technology that enables sub-linear time lookup to improve performance, as linear search is inefficient for large databases.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Suppose a database contains N data items and one must be retrieved based on the value of one of the fields.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A simple implementation retrieves and examines each item according to the test.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] If there is only one matching item, this can stop when it finds that single item, but if there are multiple matches, it must test everything.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This means that the number of operations in the average case is O(N) or linear time.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Since databases may contain many objects, and since lookup is a common operation, it is often desirable to improve performance.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index is any data structure that improves the performance of lookup.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] There are many different data structures used for this purpose.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] There are complex design trade-offs involving lookup performance, index size, and index-update performance.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Many index designs exhibit logarithmic (O(log(N))) lookup performance and in some applications it is possible to achieve flat (O(1)) performance.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indexes are used to police database constraints, such as UNIQUE, EXCLUSION, PRIMARY KEY and FOREIGN KEY.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index may be declared as UNIQUE, which creates an implicit constraint on the underlying table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Database systems usually implicitly create an index on a set of columns declared PRIMARY KEY, and some are capable of using an already-existing index to police this constraint.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Many database systems require that both referencing and referenced sets of columns in a FOREIGN KEY constraint are indexed, thus improving performance of inserts, updates and deletes to the tables participating in the constraint.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Some database systems support an EXCLUSION constraint that ensures that, for a newly inserted or updated record, a certain predicate holds for no other record.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This can be used to implement a UNIQUE constraint (with equality predicate) or more complex constraints, like ensuring that no overlapping time ranges or no intersecting geometry objects would be stored in the table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index supporting fast searching for records satisfying the predicate is required to police such a constraint.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The data is present in arbitrary order, but the **logical ordering** is specified by the index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The data rows may be spread throughout the table regardless of the value of the indexed column or expression.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The non-clustered index tree contains the index keys in sorted order, with the leaf level of the index containing the pointer to the record (page and the row number in the data page in page-organized engines; row offset in file-organized engines).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] There can be more than one non-clustered index on a database table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Clustering alters the data block into a certain distinct order to match the index, resulting in the row data being stored in order.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Therefore, only one clustered index can be created on a given database table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Clustered indexes can greatly increase overall speed of retrieval, but usually only where the data is accessed sequentially in the same or reverse order of the clustered index, or when a range of items is selected.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Since the physical records are in this sort order on disk, the next row item in the sequence is immediately before or after the last one, and so fewer data block reads are required.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The primary feature of a clustered index is therefore the ordering of the physical data rows in accordance with the index blocks that point to them.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Some databases separate the data and index blocks into separate files, others put two completely different data blocks within the same physical file(s).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] When multiple databases and multiple tables are joined, it is called a **cluster** (not to be confused with clustered index described previously).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The records for the tables sharing the value of a cluster key shall be stored together in the same or nearby data blocks.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This may improve the joins of these tables on the cluster key, since the matching records are stored together and less I/O is required to locate them.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The cluster configuration defines the data layout in the tables that are parts of the cluster.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A cluster can be keyed with a B-tree index or a hash table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The data block where the table record is stored is defined by the value of the cluster key.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The order that the index definition defines the columns in is important.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] It is possible to retrieve a set of row identifiers using only the first indexed column.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] However, it is not possible or efficient (on most databases) to retrieve the set of row identifiers using only the second or greater indexed column.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] For example, in a phone book organized by city first, then by last name, and then by first name, in a particular city, one can easily extract the list of all phone numbers.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] However, it would be very tedious to find all the phone numbers for a particular last name.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] One would have to look within each city's section for the entries with that last name.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Some databases can do this, others just won't use the index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Then a sequential lookup checks the matching with `first_name`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] So, to improve the performance, one must ensure that the index is created on the order of search columns.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indexes are useful for many applications but come with some limitations.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Consider the following SQL statement: `SELECT first_name FROM people WHERE last_name = 'Smith';`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] To process this statement without an index the database software must look at the last_name column on every row in the table (this is known as a full table scan).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] With an index the database simply follows the index data structure (typically a B-tree) until the Smith entry has been found; this is much less computationally expensive than a full table scan.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Consider this SQL statement: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE email_address LIKE '%@wikipedia.org';`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This query would yield an email address for every customer whose email address ends with "@wikipedia.org", but even if the email_address column has been indexed the database must perform a full index scan.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This is because the index is built with the assumption that words go from left to right.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] With a wildcard at the beginning of the search-term, the database software is unable to use the underlying index data structure (in other words, the WHERE-clause is *not sargable*).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This problem can be solved through the addition of another index created on `reverse(email_address)` and a SQL query like this: `SELECT email_address FROM customers WHERE reverse(email_address) LIKE reverse('%@wikipedia.org');`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This puts the wild-card at the right-most part of the query (now gro.aidepikiw@%), which the index on reverse(email_address) can satisfy.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] When the wildcard characters are used on both sides of the search word as *%wikipedia.org%*, the index available on this field is not used.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Rather only a sequential search is performed, which takes ⁠ $O(N)$ ⁠ time.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] To mitigate this, a full-text indexing approach can be used.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A bitmap index is a special kind of indexing that stores the bulk of its data as bit arrays (bitmaps) and answers most queries by performing bitwise logical operations on these bitmaps.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The most commonly used indexes, such as B+ trees, are most efficient if the values they index do not repeat or repeat a small number of times.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In contrast, the bitmap index is designed for cases where the values of a variable repeat very frequently.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] For example, the sex field in a customer database usually contains at most three distinct values: male, female or unknown (not recorded).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] For such variables, the bitmap index can have a significant performance advantage over the commonly used trees.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A dense index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every record in the data file.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer to *a record* in the sorted data file.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the dense index points *to the first record* with that key.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A sparse index in databases is a file with pairs of keys and pointers for every block in the data file.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Every key in this file is associated with a particular pointer *to the block* in the sorted data file.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In clustered indices with duplicate keys, the sparse index points *to the lowest search key* in each block.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A reverse-key index reverses the key value before entering it in the index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Reversing the key value is particularly useful for indexing data such as sequence numbers, where new key values monotonically increase.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An inverted index maps a content word to the document containing it, thereby allowing full-text searches.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The primary index contains the key fields of the table and a pointer to the non-key fields of the table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] The primary index is created automatically when the table is created in the database.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] It is used to index fields that are neither ordering fields nor key fields (there is no assurance that the file is organized on key field or primary key field).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] One index entry for every tuple in the data file (dense index) contains the value of the indexed attribute and pointer to the block or record.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Another type of index used in database systems is linear hashing.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indices can be implemented using a variety of data structures.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Popular indices include balanced trees, B+ trees and hashes.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In Microsoft SQL Server, the leaf node of the clustered index corresponds to the actual data, not simply a pointer to data that resides elsewhere, as is the case with a non-clustered index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Each relation can have a single clustered index and many unclustered indices.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] An index is typically being accessed concurrently by several transactions and processes, and thus needs concurrency control.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] While in principle indexes can utilize the common database concurrency control methods, specialized concurrency control methods for indexes exist, which are applied in conjunction with the common methods for a substantial performance gain.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In most cases, an index is used to quickly locate the data records from which the required data is read.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] In other words, the index is only used to locate data records in the table and not to return data.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A covering index is a special case where the index itself contains the required data fields and can answer the required data.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] To find the Name for ID 13, an index on (ID) is useful, but the record must still be read to get the Name.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] However, an index on (ID, Name) contains the required data field and eliminates the need to look up the record.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Covering indexes are each for a specific table.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Queries which JOIN/ access across multiple tables, may potentially consider covering indexes on more than one of these tables.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] A covering index can dramatically speed up data retrieval but may itself be large due to the additional keys, which slow down data insertion and update.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] To reduce such index size, some systems allow including non-key fields in the index.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Non-key fields are not themselves part of the index ordering but only included at the leaf level, allowing for a covering index with less overall index size.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] This can be done in SQL with `CREATE INDEX my_index ON my_table (id) INCLUDE (name);`.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] No standard defines how to create indexes, because the ISO SQL Standard does not cover physical aspects.
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] Indexes are one of the physical parts of database conception among others like storage (tablespace or filegroups).
[src:apache-parquet/database-index] RDBMS vendors all give a `CREATE INDEX` syntax with some specific options that depend on their software's capabilities.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] When the encoder finds such a match, it substitutes a reference to the string's position in the data structure.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Some dictionary coders use a 'static dictionary', one whose full set of strings is determined before coding begins and does not change during the coding process.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] This scheme of using Huffman coding to represent indices into a concordance has been called "Huffword".
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] In a related and more general method, a dictionary is built from redundancy extracted from a data environment (various input streams) which dictionary is then used statically to compress a further input stream.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] For example, a dictionary is built from old English texts then is used to compress a book.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] More common are methods where the dictionary starts in some predetermined state but the contents change during the encoding process, based on the data that has already been encoded.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Both the LZ77 and LZ78 algorithms work on this principle.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] In LZ77, a circular buffer called the "sliding window" holds the last *N* bytes of data processed.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] This window serves as the dictionary, effectively storing *every* substring that has appeared in the past *N* bytes as dictionary entries.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Instead of a single index identifying a dictionary entry, two values are needed: the *length*, indicating the length of the matched text, and the *offset* (also called the *distance*), indicating that the match is found in the sliding window starting *offset* bytes before the current text.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] LZ78 uses a more explicit dictionary structure; at the beginning of the encoding process, the dictionary is empty.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] An index value of zero is used to represent the end of a string, so the first index of the dictionary is one.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] At each step of the encoding process, if there is no match, then the last matching index (or zero) and character are both added to the dictionary and output to the compressed stream.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] If there is a match, then the working index is updated to the matching index, and nothing is output.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] LZW is similar to LZ78, but, the dictionary is initialized to all possible symbols.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] The typical implementation works with 8 bit symbols, so the dictionary "codes" for hex 00 to hex FF (decimal 255) are pre-defined.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Dictionary entries would be added starting with code value hex 100.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Unlike LZ78, if a match is not found (or if the end of data), then only the dictionary code is output.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] This creates a potential issue since the decoder output is one step behind the dictionary.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Enhancements to LZW include handing symbol sizes other than 8 bits and having reserved codes to reset the dictionary and to indicate end of data.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] Brotli is an example of a commonly used coder that is initialised with a pre-defined dictionary, but later goes on to use more sophisticated content modelling.
[src:apache-parquet/dictionary-coder] The Brotli dictionary consists largely of natural-language words and HTML and JavaScript fragments, based on an analysis of web traffic.
